TY  - JOUR
AU  - Almeida, I.S.
AU  - Pinto, C.
AU  - Lima, A.
AU  - Moreira, T.
AU  - Fernandes, C.S.
TI  - Game4NurseSupervisor: Development of a board game for nursing mentoring
PY  - 2024
JO  - Nurse Education in Practice
DO  - 10.1016/j.nepr.2024.103939
AB  - Aim: To describe the stages of developing a board game prototype to promote knowledge about nursing mentorship. Background: Clinical supervision in nursing is a vital strategy for the quality of care. The use of gamification through a board game can enhance knowledge about mentoring in nursing. Design: We present a pilot study describing the development phases of the board game “Game4NurseSupervisor®.” Methods: The study comprised three phases. The first phase involved a modified e-Delphi study with experts to collect and validate the content to be integrated into the board game. The second phase focused on constructing the prototype of the board game. Finally, the third phase involved testing the prototype in sessions held in two healthcare units, followed by an evaluation through a questionnaire. Results: The e-Delphi study, involving a panel composed of 59 experts, progressed through two rounds, resulting in 61 cards divided into four categories. The second phase involved constructing the board game, incorporating interactive elements such as “Game4NurseSupervisor®.” In the third phase, 25 nurses, consisting of clinical practice nurses, participated in the testing phase and expressed satisfaction with the game. Highlighted benefits included reflective, playful, dynamic, interactive and educational aspects. Conclusions: The conclusions suggest that “Game4NurseSupervisor®” could be a valuable tool for promoting knowledge about nursing mentorship, providing an innovative and interactive approach to skill development. This study makes a valuable contribution by addressing a previously unexplored aspect of nurse mentor training: the potential of board games. © 2024
ER  -

TY  - JOUR
AU  - José María, E.-F.
AU  - Esteve-Faubel, R.P.
AU  - Chust-Pérez, V.
AU  - Botella-Quirant, M.T.
TI  - Fostering soft skills through collaborative music projects in the initial education stage of primary teachers
PY  - 2025
JO  - Social Sciences and Humanities Open
DO  - 10.1016/j.ssaho.2025.101681
AB  - This study examines the development of soft skills in pre-service primary education teachers through a project-based learning (PBL) intervention using the ICT tool Book Creator within a Music in Primary Education course. Acknowledging the growing significance of non-technical skills such as communication, teamwork, and adaptability for 21st-century educators, this research explores the effectiveness of PBL in fostering these competencies. A qualitative, exploratory approach was adopted, employing focus groups to analyse the experiences of 104 students over three academic years. The findings highlight PBL's transformative potential in developing essential soft skills, shifting students from passive recipients to active content creators. Notably, autonomy, self-confidence, commitment, resilience, empathy, and problem-solving abilities were significantly enhanced through collaborative tasks and reflective practices. Students reported increased motivation, improved teamwork, and a deeper understanding of the interplay between hard and soft skills. The study underscores the importance of structured guidance, peer learning, and extracurricular activities in supporting soft skill development. This research advocates for a holistic competency framework in teacher training that integrates technical proficiency with socio-emotional intelligence, aligning with frameworks such as CASEL and UNESCO's Education 2030. It emphasises the need for teaching models that harness digital tools to promote innovation, collaboration, and critical thinking, preparing future educators for increasingly dynamic and digital classrooms. Further research should explore alternative assessment methods and investigate the potential of emerging technologies such as AI and VR in enhancing interpersonal skills. © 2025
